% This file  contains some LaTeX2e  style  definitions (page width and height,   %
% spacing, margins etc.) that are standard     for all papers submitted to the   %
% Young Scientists Conference "Problems of Theoretic and Applied Mathematics".   %
%                                                                                %
% Attention! You should write  a title  of your  paper only with the command:    %
%   \atitle{Arg1}{Arg2}[Arg3]                                                    %
% where                                                                          %
%   Arg1              - a title of paper,                                        %
%   Arg2              - name(s) of author(s) (syntax: last name + initials)      %
%   Arg3 (optional)   - papers attributes for contents (default is Arg2 + Arg1)  %
%                                                                                %
% Please, pay your attention to interesting theorem-like environments, that are  %
% defined below with the commands \newtheorem. To write  (and properly decorate) %
% your theorem (statement, definition, etc.) your may  use one of predefined     %
% environments:                                                                  %
%    \begin{thm} ... text of a theorem     ... \end{thm}   -  for a theorem      %
%    \begin{stm} ... text of a statement   ... \end{stm}   -  for a statement    %
%    \begin{prop}... text of a proposition ... \end{prop}  -  for a proposition  %
%    \begin{defi}... text of a definition  ... \end{defi}  -  for a definition   %
%    \begin{cor} ... text of a corollary   ... \end{cor}   -  for a corollary.   %
%    \begin{rem} ... text of a remark      ... \end{rem}   -  for a remark.      %
% Using these environments you may not care of titles or numbers of              %
%    your theorems.                                                              %
% If your paper contains only one theorem and you needn't number it, please, use %
% one of these environments with a star. For example, to decorate the only       %
% theorem simple write:                                                          %
%  \begin{thm*} ... text ... \end{thm*}                                          %
